# TypeScript Style Guide

## Overview

These guidelines establish TypeScript-specific patterns and best practices for maintaining clean, type-safe, and maintainable code.

## Related Guidelines

- [React](./react.mdc) - React development guidelines
- [Testing](./testing.mdc) - Testing guidelines and practices

## Type System

### Type Annotations

1. Explicit Types:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Explicit types for public APIs
   function processUser(user: User): ProcessedUser {
     return { ...user, lastProcessed: new Date() };
   }

   // ❌ Bad - Relying on inference for public APIs
   function processUser(user) {
     return { ...user, lastProcessed: new Date() };
   }
   ```

2. Type Inference:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Let TypeScript infer obvious types
   const users = ['Alice', 'Bob']; // string[]

   // ❌ Bad - Redundant type annotation
   const users: string[] = ['Alice', 'Bob'];
   ```

### Type Definitions

1. Use `type` over `interface`:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Type for object types
   type User = {
     id: string;
     name: string;
     email: string;
   };

   // ✅ Good - Type for unions/intersections
   type Status = 'active' | 'inactive';
   ```

2. Generic Types:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Descriptive type parameters
   type Repository<TEntity> = {
     findById(id: string): Promise<TEntity>;
   };

   // ❌ Bad - Single-letter type parameters
   type Repository<T> = {
     findById(id: string): Promise<T>;
   };
   ```

## React TypeScript

### Component Types

1. Function Components:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Explicit prop interface
   type UserCardProps = {
     user: User;
     onEdit?: (user: User) => void;
   };

   function UserCard({ user, onEdit }: UserCardProps) {
     return (/* ... */);
   }
   ```

2. Generic Components:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Reusable generic components
   type ListProps<T> = {
     items: T[];
     renderItem: (item: T) => React.ReactNode;
   };

   function List<T>({ items, renderItem }: ListProps<T>) {
     return (/* ... */);
   }
   ```

### Event Handlers

1. Event Types:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Proper event typing
   function handleChange(event: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) {
     const value = event.target.value;
   }

   // ❌ Bad - any type for events
   function handleChange(event: any) {
     const value = event.target.value;
   }
   ```

2. Handler Types:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Explicit handler types
   type SubmitHandler = (data: FormData) => Promise<void>;

   const handleSubmit: SubmitHandler = async (data) => {
     await submitForm(data);
   };
   ```

## State Management

### Type-Safe State

1. Zustand Store:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Type-safe store
   type AppState = {
     user: User | null;
     setUser: (user: User | null) => void;
   };

   const useStore = create<AppState>((set) => ({
     user: null,
     setUser: (user) => set({ user }),
   }));
   ```

2. React Query:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Typed queries
   function useUser(id: string) {
     return useQuery<User, Error>({
       queryKey: ['user', id],
       queryFn: () => fetchUser(id),
     });
   }
   ```

## API Integration

### Type-Safe API Calls

1. Request/Response Types:

   ```typescript
   type CreateUserRequest = {
     name: string;
     email: string;
   };

   type CreateUserResponse = {
     id: string;
     name: string;
     email: string;
     createdAt: string;
   };

   async function createUser(
     data: CreateUserRequest,
   ): Promise<CreateUserResponse> {
     const response = await fetch('/api/users', {
       method: 'POST',
       body: JSON.stringify(data),
     });
     return response.json();
   }
   ```

2. Error Types:

   ```typescript
   type ApiError = {
     code: string;
     message: string;
     details?: Record<string, unknown>;
   };

   async function fetchData<T>(url: string): Promise<T> {
     const response = await fetch(url);
     if (!response.ok) {
       const error: ApiError = await response.json();
       throw new Error(error.message);
     }
     return response.json();
   }
   ```

## Forms

### Type-Safe Forms

1. Form Data Types:

   ```typescript
   type LoginForm = {
     email: string;
     password: string;
     rememberMe: boolean;
   };

   function LoginForm() {
     const form = useForm<LoginForm>({
       defaultValues: {
         email: '',
         password: '',
         rememberMe: false,
       },
     });
   }
   ```

2. Validation Schema:

   ```typescript
   const loginSchema = z.object({
     email: z.string().email(),
     password: z.string().min(8),
     rememberMe: z.boolean(),
   });

   type LoginForm = z.infer<typeof loginSchema>;
   ```

## Type Safety Best Practices

### Strict Mode

1. Enable Strict Mode:

   ```json
   {
     "compilerOptions": {
       "strict": true,
       "noImplicitAny": true,
       "strictNullChecks": true,
       "strictFunctionTypes": true,
       "strictBindCallApply": true,
       "strictPropertyInitialization": true,
       "noImplicitThis": true,
       "useUnknownInCatchVariables": true
     }
   }
   ```

### Type Guards

1. Custom Type Guards:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Type guard function
   function isUser(value: unknown): value is User {
     return (
       typeof value === 'object' &&
       value !== null &&
       'id' in value &&
       'name' in value
     );
   }

   // Usage
   if (isUser(data)) {
     console.log(data.name); // TypeScript knows data is User
   }
   ```

### Utility Types

1. Built-in Utility Types:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Using utility types
   type UserUpdate = Partial<User>;
   type UserReadOnly = Readonly<User>;
   type UserKeys = keyof User;
   type UserPick = Pick<User, 'id' | 'name'>;
   type UserOmit = Omit<User, 'password'>;
   ```
